Implemented a custom PrunableLinear layer where each weight is paired with a learnable gate parameter.
Gates are passed through a sigmoid function to constrain values between 0 and 1, and multiplied with weights to enable differentiable pruning.
The model is trained on the CIFAR-10 dataset using a standard feed-forward architecture.
Introduced a modified loss function:
Total Loss = Cross-Entropy Loss + λ × Sparsity Loss
The sparsity loss is computed as the L1 norm of all gate values, encouraging many gates to become zero.
L1 regularization promotes sparsity by applying constant pressure that pushes gate values toward exact zero.
Experiments conducted with multiple λ values show:
Low λ → higher accuracy, lower sparsity
High λ → higher sparsity, reduced accuracy
Sparsity is measured as the percentage of gates below a threshold (e.g., 1e-2).
Final gate distribution shows:
A large number of values near 0 (pruned weights)
A smaller cluster near 1 (important weights)
The model successfully demonstrates dynamic architecture learning, pruning unnecessary connections during training without requiring a separate pruning step.
